The use of continue statement in nested loop is an important application of this statement. It helps in skipping unprocessed rows when they are known to be unchanged or invalid and process only changed ones, as shown below:
```
i = 1;
while i <= x.LastRow do
     if x[i]._RowState != RS_CHANGED then
          i = i + 1;
          continue;
     endif;
     /* Process row */
     i = i + 1;
endwhile;
```
In the above code, a nested loop is used to process only changed rows in a table. The outer while loop iterates over all rows in the table. The inner while loop processes each row and skips unprocessed ones when they are known to be unchanged or invalid.

